The Argentine government will askcongress to declare a state of siege following a rebellion byarmy officers objecting to human rights trials, officialsources said.    Earlier, Army Chief of Staff Hector Rios Erenu said hewould use all the means at his disposal to put down therebellion. He relieved from their commands two colonels, one ofthem at an airborne infantry regiment in Cordoba, centre of theuprising.    Argentine Army Chief of Staff Hector Rios Erenu said hewould begin moving troops for a possible military operation toput down the almost three-day old rebellion.    Interior Minister Antonio Troccoli said the governmentwould seek parliamentary approval of the state of siege "unlessthere is something unexpected that justifies more urgenttreatment." Reuter&#3;